Annals of Nuclear Energy

Volume 155, 1 June 2021, 108165

Numerical analysis of liquid fall type gas entrainment in pool-type fast reactor

Author links open overlay panel, , , , Guanghui Su, , Suizheng Qiu
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.anucene.2021.108165Get rights and content

Highlights

  • •

    The process of liquid fall type entrainment on free surface was described in detail.

  • •

    The parameters affecting the entrainment were analyzed respectively.

  • •

    The conservative criterion for the sodium-argon entrainment was obtained.

  • •

    An entrainment prediction method for Sodium-cooled fast reactors (SFRs) was provided.

Abstract

Argon covering the free surface of the pool-type sodium-cooled fast reactor may be mixed into the coolant in form of entrainment bubbles due to the fluctuation of liquid surface, which introduces positive reactivity to the core, reduces the heat exchange capacity of the core and intermediate heat exchangers (IHXs), and possibly leads to the cavitation of the primary sodium pump (PSP), threatening the safe operation of the reactor. In this study, the computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulation of liquid sodium fall entrained argon was carried out based on the Volume of Fluid (VOF) interface tracking method to describe the entrainment process in detail, and the influences of geometry size, initial liquid level height and inlet velocity on entrainment were analyzed successively. It was found that the re-submergence velocity, having a linear relation with the re-submergence angle, is the key factor of the liquid fall type gas entrainment. It can be used to judge whether the liquid fall type entrainment occurs conservatively. In addition, the parameters affecting the re-submergence velocity are specifically analyzed from the supplementary cases, according to the results of which, the empirical relation of the re-submergence velocity is obtained. Therefore, the situation of liquid fall type gas entrainment under various working conditions can be predicted numerically.

1. Introduction

Sodium-cooled fast reactor (SFR) has been regarded as one of the most promising reactors in the fourth-generation nuclear reactors due to its outstanding advantages in nuclear fuel proliferation, long-life actinide element evolution and inherent safety as well as its rich operating experience and technical accumulation (Abram and Ion, 2008). Liquid sodium, as one of the coolants in fast breeder reactors (FBRs), has high thermal conductivity and high boiling point, which makes SFR have a compact core with high heat flux and high thermal conversion efficiency. However, the active chemical property of liquid sodium does not allow contacting air directly. Consequently, all positions in FBR system containing free liquid surface need to be covered with inert gas (mainly argon) as a protective medium which can also adapt to the change of coolant volume caused by temperature variation. The covered argon may be mixed into liquid sodium in the form of entrainment bubbles due to the fluctuation of liquid surface, which is defined as the phenomenon of free surface entrainment (Baum and Cook, 1975). It may happen not only on the free surface of SFRs, but also in the ADS-4 pipe of AP1000 (Meng et al., 2017), the header-feeder geometry of CANDU reactor (Shen et al., 2020), the pipelines of passive residual heat removal system (Gu et al., 2020) and so on. For economic reasons, the structure of FBR is relatively compact, leading to increase of the flow rate of coolant, which is conducive to increase the probability of entrainment (Chellapandi and Velusamy, 2015). The free surface of pool-type SFR is much higher than that of loop-type and is more prone to entrainment. The phenomenon of entrainment is further aggravated by the coolant flow around primary sodium pump (PSP), intermediate heat exchanger (IHX), decay heat exchanger (DHX) and other structures immersed in sodium pool. According to the formation mechanism, free surface entrainment can be divided into three types: vortex type, breaking wave type and liquid fall type. The phenomenon of entrainment will not only introduce positive reactivity into core, causing power fluctuations and thus threatening safe operation of reactor, but also stagnate and accumulate bubbles in core and heat exchangers, reducing heat transfer capacity, and may also cause cavitation of PSP. Therefore, argon entrainment significantly affecting safe operation of SFR should be paid more attention to.

In view of the importance of this problem, some scholars had carried out researches on the free surface entrainment phenomenon of SFRs since the 1970s. Baum and Cook (1975) studied the influence of surface velocity, type of working fluid and surface tension on the entrainment phenomenon through small-scale mechanism experiments, and the results showed that entrainment is more likely to occur on conditions with higher surface velocity and tension, and entrainment degrees of different working fluids are mainly determined by viscosity and surface tension. Eguchi et al. (1994) performed small-scale hydraulic experiments and found that the increase of fluid viscosity could inhibit entrainment, and entrainment would only occur when its Froude number (Fr) is greater than a critical value. Kimura et al. (2008) carried out water and sodium experiments successively in the experimental device of the Japanese demonstration fast breeder reactor (DFBR) pressure vessel with a ratio of 1:1.8, and found that entrainment occurred in some areas of the hot pool due to excessive vertical velocity. Patwardhan et al. (2012) built a series of small-scale mechanism experimental devices and the SAMRAT water platform for Indian prototype fast breeder reactor (PFBR) hot sodium pool with a ratio of 1:4, aiming at uncovering mechanisms and influencing factors of different entrainment types in detail. Banerjee et al. (2013) built a 1/4 small-scale water platform of PFBR primary circuit with heating capacity and carried out a three-dimensional steady-state simulation of the sodium pool. According to their research, an optimized design scheme was proposed to significantly reduce the entrainment occurrence by adding horizontal plates to the inner wall of the sodium pool. Guenadou et al., 2016, Tenchine et al., 2014) built a series of water platforms with different ratios from 1:10 to 1:2, named PLATEAU, MICAS, OREILLETTE and COLCHIX respectively, to simulate flow and entrainment of hot pool, core plenum, IHX and other assemblies of advanced European prototype fast reactor (ASTRID). From the results of experiments, they got the probabilities of entrainment occurred under different working conditions and found that free surface height had little influence on width and size of vortices. The generation source of vortices is mainly Karman Vortex Street generated behind PSP, IHXs and other submerged structures when liquid flows around them. Cristofano et al. (2014) set up a small transparent water tank for mechanical experimental bench to study the influence of parameters such as water level, diameter of drainage outlet and drainage flow rate on the generation and development of free surface entrainment, and preliminarily provided a similarity modeling criterion for water to replace sodium in entrainment experiments. Moudjed et al. (2016) used a water platform named BANGA for mechanism experimental research, innovatively adding obstacles with different shapes and sizes in the end of the import section to simulate inlet boundary conditions for free surface entrainment, and proposed a data processing method of particle image velocimetry (PIV) images, where void fraction, surface velocity field and gas volume fraction of drainage could be obtained. Ezure et al. (2019) obtained the relationship between the free surface dimple shape of vortex type entrainment and the velocity distribution around the free surface vorticity under different conditions through PIV, and the obtained quantitative relationship can be used to verify the evaluation model of entrainment. Pandazis and Babcsany (2016) studied the formation process of surface vortices through numerical simulation, compared with the experimental results obtained by a high-speed camera, and proposed a method to predict the critical submergence depth. However, there are not many specific studies on liquid fall type entrainment, and the important references are as follows. Madarame and Chiba (1990) proved that surface fluctuation is not directly related to the liquid level but related to re-submergence velocity or re-submergence angle and liquid fall type entrainment will not occur when (Fr•We)0.25 < 2, by the water-air entrainment experiments in a tank. Hagiwara et al. (1991) conducted similar experiments and made the conclusion that both re-submergence velocity and re-submergence angle affect liquid fall type entrainment: when the re-submergence velocity is less than 0.8 m/s, the re-submergence angle is 12°; when the re-submergence angle is more than 12°, the entrainment occurs; when the re-submergence velocity is more than 0.8 m/s, the re-submergence angle decreases. From a two-dimensional CFD simulation, Satpathy et al. (2013) found the phenomenon of water entraining air will not appear when the free surface velocity is less than 0.315 m/s, which basically conform to the criterion of Ref. Madarame and Chiba (1990). After that, the width and the position of the baffle in the Indian PFBR were optimized to suppress entrainment by three-dimensional steady-state CFD calculations with a model of quarter hot pool. In general, previous works have studied the phenomenon of entrapment from different aspects. Different types of entrainment, having distinctive formation mechanisms and influence factors, need to be studied separately. Furthermore, researches of liquid fall type entrainment are relatively less than those of other types. Due to the complex mechanism of entrainment, the research results are restricted to experimental working medium, measurement mean and computing capacity, and only relatively conservative conclusions can be obtained. Thus, the phenomenon of liquid sodium fall entraining argon in free surface of pool-type sodium-cooled fast reactor was studied in this paper. According to CFD simulation results, occurrence criterion and regularity of this phenomenon were analyzed to obtain more accurate conclusions.

2. Solution methodology

2.1. Governing equations

The Reynolds-Average Navier-Stokes (RANS) equation and the continuity equation for incompressible fluid entrainment are as follows:(1)ρ∂u¯i∂t+u¯j∂u¯i∂xj=-∂p¯∂xi+∂∂xjμ∂u¯i∂xj-ρui′uj′¯(2)∂ui∂xi=0where -ρui′uj′ refers to the term of Reynolds stresses, representing the time-averaged pulsation momentum through unit control area per unit time. The model based on the RANS equation set makes assumptions for Reynolds stresses, namely establishing the constitutive relations of various empirical and semi-empirical formulas, to close the turbulent Reynolds-Average equation set. Among all those assumptions, the vortex-viscous closed method, Boussinesq hypothesis, is widely and commonly applied in engineering turbulence. It was proposed by Boussinesq along the same idea of molecular viscosity, which relates the Reynolds stresses to the average velocity gradients:(3)ui′uj′¯=-νt∂ui∂xj+∂uj∂xi-23∂uk∂xkδij+23kδijwhere(4)νt=μtρwhere νt and μt are the kinematic viscosity and dynamic viscosity of turbulence (or eddy), respectively. When the average velocity gradient is known, the six Reynolds stresses can be determined by the turbulence kinematic viscosity (νt) which is hypothesized to be isotropic and can be modeled by additional turbulence parameters. As same as other k-ε models, the Realizable k-ε model introduces two additional turbulence parameters, the turbulence kinetic energy (k) and the turbulence dissipation rate (ε), in order to close the governing equation set, requiring solving two additional differential equations simultaneously. The turbulence (or eddy) dynamic viscosity (μt) is computed as follows:(5)μt=ρCμk2ε

Differing from the standard and RNG k-ε models, Cμ of the Realizable k-ε model is no longer a constant and is calculated by:(6)Cμ=1A0+ASkU∗εwhere(7)U∗≡SijSij+(Ωij¯-3εijkωk)(Ωij¯-3εijkωk)where Ω¯ij is the mean rate-of-rotation tensor viewed in a moving reference frame with the angular velocity (ωk), and model constants (A0 and AS) are given by:(8)A0=4.04,AS=6cosφwhere(9)φ=13cos-16W,W=SijSjkSki(SijSij)3,Sij=12∂ui∂xj+∂uj∂xi

The turbulence kinetic energy (k) and the turbulence dissipation rate (ε) of Eq. (5) are obtained from the following transport equations:(10)∂∂tρk+∂∂xjρkμj=∂∂xjμ+μtσk∂k∂xj+Gk+Gb-ρε-YM+Sk(11)∂∂tρε+∂∂xjρεμj=∂∂xjμ+μtσε∂ε∂xj+ρC1Sε-ρC2ε2k+νε+ρC1εεkC3εGb+Sε

The model constants should be set reasonably to ensure that the model performs well for some typical flows. Generally, the constants of model selected in the above equations are: C1ε = 1.44, C2 = 1.9, σk = 1.0, σε = 1.2.

The VOF model can model two or more immiscible fluids by solving a single set of momentum equations and tracking the volume fraction of each of the fluids throughout the domain. The value of the nth fluid’s volume fraction (αn) in a cell can be classified into three possibilities under different situations:(12)αn=0,thecellisemptyofthenthfluid0<αn<1,thecellistheinterfaceofthenthfluidαn=1,thecellisfullofthenthfluid

Based on the local value of αn, the appropriate properties and variables will be assigned to each control volume within the domain, which accounts for the necessity that refined mesh ensures the accuracy of interface simulation results. The tracking of the interface(s) between the phases is accomplished by the solution of a continuity equation for the volume fraction of one (or more) of the phases. This equation of the nth fluid is:(13)1ρn∂∂tαnρn+∇·αnρnvn→=∑m=1N(mmn·-mnm·)

where ṁmn is the mass transfer from phase m to phase n, and ṁnm is the mass transfer from phase n to phase m. Combined with the constraint of the primary-phase volume fraction: ∑n=1Nαn=1, the volume fraction equation may be solved either through implicit or explicit time formulation. The velocity field shared among the phases is obtained from a single momentum equation throughout the domain:(14)∂∂tρv→+∇·ρv→v→=-∇p+∇·μ∇v→+∇v→T+ρg→where physical properties (density ρ and dynamic viscosity μ) are calculated according to volume-averaged method:(15)ρ=∑n=1Nαnρn,μ=∑n=1Nαnμnwhere ρn and μn are the density and the dynamic viscosity of the nth fluid. The surface tension, the force acting only at the surface, is to balance the radially inward inter-molecular attractive force with the radially outward pressure gradient force across the surface, modeled by the continuum surface force (CSF) model proposed by Brackbill et al. (1992). As for the interface of two phases, the pressure drop across the surface depends upon the surface tension coefficient (σ) and the surface curvatures as measured by the radii in the two orthogonal directions (R1 and R2):(16)△p=p2-p1=σ1R1+1R2where P1 and P2 are the pressures of two fluids on either side of the interface. If n→ is defined as the surface normal gradient of the volume fraction of the nth phase, that is n→=∇αn, then the curvature (κ) defined in terms of the divergence of the unit normal can be denoted as κ=∇·n→|n→|. For a two-phases system, κ1=-κ2 and ∇α1=-∇α2, then the volume force is simplified as surface tension source term for a cell which is proportional to the average density in the cell:(17)Fvol=σ2ρκ1∇α1ρ1+ρ2where ρ1 and ρ2 are the densities of two phases. The Pressure Implicit with Splitting of Operators (PISO) algorithm, which is more suitable for the unsteady flow, is employed to solve the pressure–velocity coupling between the incompressible Navier–Stokes and continuity equations. For flow simulation in high curvature computational region, ‘PRESTO!’ is recommended for the spatial discretization of pressure. According to the volume fraction of the interface between phases, geometry reconstruction is conducted on the liquid surface to realize accurate interface tracking.

2.2. Applicability verification for VOF model

The interaction between gas-liquid two phases is the key point to focus on in the phenomenon of liquid sodium fall entraining argon in SFR hot pool. As a method to capture the interface, the VOF model is a good choice for handling viscous fluid problems with complex free surfaces. As a benchmark for free surface flow, the dam break problem is widely mentioned in experimental and simulative studies by experts and scholars. Thereby, the dam break problem is used to verify the applicability of VOF in this entrainment study. As described in Ref. Koshizuka and Oka (1996), the experimental device for this problem is an open tank with a length of 4L and a height of 3L. Before the experiment, the water on the left side is maintained within location range of a width of L and a height of 2L, as shown in Fig. 1. The transient simulation results of the dam break are compared as shown in Fig. 2 and the curves of water level height on the left wall over time are drawn in Fig. 3. All of these indicate that the simulation results are in good agreement with previous experimental and simulative results, verifying the reasonability of employing VOF model in this kind of problem.

3. Simulation of argon entrainment

3.1. 2D model simulations

The process of liquid sodium fall entraining argon on free surface in SFR hot pool was simulated numerically, the vital results of which are utilized to summarize the occurrence criterion and regularity of this phenomenon. The upper part of a typical hot pool is nearly cylinder with a control plug (CP), two PSPs, four IHXs and four DHXs. These devices immersed in the hot pool make it inapplicable to use the 2D axisymmetric swirl model, but necessary to build at least a 1/4 3D model (Fig. 4a) for the hot pool simulation. However, entrainment needs a transient simulation with VOF model, which requires a high calculation capacity especially for a 3D model. These devices will intensify fluid flowing around and then enhance the likelihood of entrainment. As for liquid fall type gas entrainment, the longitudinal section which consists of both axes of the CP and the IHX (Fig. 4b) is regarded as the characteristic plane. Moreover, the region contained by the red dash line in Fig. 4b is the dominant region to focus on. Thereby, a simplified 2D model, as shown in Fig. 4c, can be obtained after the dimensions of this geometry are scaled down by about twenty times, and be denoted as Case 1. The liquid flows in with a speed of Vin through the inlet at the bottom of the left wall and out through the outlet at a height of Ho from bottom of the right wall, which simulates whole process that coolant enters through axial gap between core and control plug, thus turns to horizontally flow into hot pool and leaves hot pool from windows of IHX eventually. The heights of the inlet and outlet of tank are denoted as hi and ho respectively. W is the width of hot pool, H is the height of hot pool and Hl is the initial height of liquid level. The fluids selected are argon and liquid sodium, the main physical properties of which are listed in Table 1. The Continuum Surface Force (CSF) model is chosen for considering surface tension between two phases. The surface tension coefficient for argon-sodium is taken as 156.111mN/m. The turbulence model adopts the most widely applicable one, the Realizable k-ε model. The surrounding walls are set as no-slid stationary walls. The inlet and outlet are imposed with a constant velocity boundary condition and a constant pressure boundary condition respectively. PISO scheme is used for the coupled solution of pressure and velocity. The residuals of continuity equation and momentum equations are set as 10e−4. The time step size is obtained by CFL condition. The reference pressure is set in the argon above the liquid surface, so the height of hot pool (H) has very little influence on the calculated results. When the height of hot pool (H) is 10 ~ 20 mm higher than the highest liquid level in the whole entrainment process, it can be considered that the height of hot pool (H) does not affect the entrainment. Under this situation, it is established as minimal as possible in order to reduce the amount of meshes. Because of the simplified geometry and better calculation of surface tension, a structured quadrilateral grid is established. As for all the cases with boundary conditions of Vin = 1 m/s and Hl = 70 mm, the grid size is taken as 0.3 ~ 1.5 mm for the grid-independence analysis. All of these analyses showed the similar results, so the analysis process of Case 1 is selected as the typical representation. The correlation between calculated result and grid number is exhibited in Fig. 5. When the grid size is 0.5 mm, the re-submergence velocity and the re-submergence angle are 0.769 m/s and 56.35°, which vary only 0.13% and 0.52% respectively, compared with 0.77 m /s and 56.06° when the grid size is 0.3 mm. Thus, it can be considered that numerical calculation results are independent of the grid size. From another point of view, the bubble diameter produced by entrainment is usually in the range of 1 mm to several mm, so it is reasonable to choose the grid size of 0.5 mm. All the mesh qualities are higher than 0.97, and 89.4% of them arrive 0.998. In vicinity area of the non-sliding walls, boundary layer mesh refining is implemented with y+ within the range of 20 ~ 30. In addition, time step sensitivity analysis is also conducted, and the results are shown in Fig. 6. It can be seen that there are only small differences between the calculated results with 0.5 ms time step size obtained from CFL condition and those with smaller sizes. So it can be considered that simulation results are irrelevant to the time step size decided by CFL condition. Because the outlet is imposed with a constant pressure boundary condition, the outlet size has little influence on entrainment and does not need to take into consideration. The cases with different parameters, such as the height of outlet position (Ho), the initial height of liquid level (Hl), the width of hot pool (W), the inlet size (hi) and the inlet velocity (Vin), were numerically calculated for qualitative research on influence of each variable and foundation for subsequent quantitative research. The cases are listed in Table 2 in detail.

3.2. Simulation results

3.2.1. Dynamic generating process of argon entrainment

The entire process of liquid fall type entrainment can usually be divided into the initialization stage, the beginning stage, the development stage and the re-submerging stage in chronological order, as shown in Fig. 7.

  • •

    The initialization stage: this stage is the initial status of calculation when the fluid is at rest.

  • •

    The beginning stage: the fluid flowing from the inlet into the container causes the left liquid level to rise, and partial fluid close to the outlet flowing out causes the right liquid level to drop slightly.

  • •

    The development stage: the entering fluid first flows to the right side along the bottom of tank, and then gradually changes to flow upward along the right wall under the impact of the right wall and causes the right free surface to swell. The velocity of free surface also gradually reduces with kinetic energy transferring to potential energy. The left liquid level goes down continuously during this stage.

  • •

    The re-submerging stage: the free surface swell falls down from the upper right to the lower left with the liquid level reducing and the velocity continuing to increase. In this process, the free surface is drastically distorted or even discontinuous, which may lead to the phenomenon under some circumstances.

  • •

    The entrainment phenomenon: entrainment is considered to occur when at least one bubble is involved into free surface of fluid. The point where the bubble is involved is called re-submerging point. The falling liquid forms a relatively stagnant region on the left of this point.

All the calculated cases were divided into three categories, namely, entrainment, just a little entrainment and no entrainment, according to the volume of entrained gas. The numerical calculation results are listed in Table 3. What needs to be pointed out is that the data were read at the moment before entrainment is about to occur in the entrainment cases or at the moment when maximum distortion of free surface is taken in the no-entrainment cases. Another thing to be noted is that maximum surface velocity is defined as re-submergence velocity (Vms), so location of this velocity is selected for recording data of results. Usually, the selected location is not the re-submerging point where the entrainment occurs, but a certain position on the right of it. The reason is that the liquid falls down from a high place, the potential energy being converted into kinetic energy to increase the velocity continuously. However, when it encounters the incoming liquid from the other side near the re-submerging point, the effect of increasing velocity is suppressed and the velocity consequently goes down. Ultimately, the minimum velocity and the maximum turbulence kinetic energy are got at the re-submerging point. When the entrainment occurs, the free surface near the re-submerging point is violently distorted, and the velocity and turbulence kinetic energy soar in a very short time and then plunge rapidly. There are some uncertainties in the selection of time and location for no-entrainment cases, especially case with larger pool width (W) and higher inlet turbulence intensity (namely smaller inlet velocity Vin or larger inlet size hi) such as Case 5 and subsequent supplementary Case 11. The free surface fluctuations caused by multiple encounters of liquids on both sides will happen in these cases which are called as deviation cases subsequently. Therefore, it is vital significant to select appropriate cases for analysis to reduce errors in data reading so as to enhance persuasion of conclusions. Taking the conditions with 1 m/s and 0.6 m/s inlet velocity (Vin) of Case 1 as the examples of entrainment and no-entrainment, Fig. 8 shows the variations of velocity and turbulence kinetic energy at the data reading points of the free surfaces over time, and Fig. 9 shows the spatial distributions of velocity and turbulence kinetic energy at the data reading moments.

3.2.2. Conservative entrainment criterion

The dependences of re-submergence angle (θ) and turbulence kinetic energy (k) on re-submergence velocity (Vms) of Case 1–4 were plotted as Fig. 10. It obvious that an intuitive conservative entrainment criterion can be obtained: entrainment will not occur when the re-submergence velocity (Vms) is less than 0.56 m/s, turbulence kinetic energy (k) is less than 0.06 m2/s2, or the re-submergence angle (θ) is less than 37°, or Fr2•We is less than 55. In addition, it can be seen that the re-submergence angle (θ) is basically proportional to the re-submergence velocity (Vms), which is consistent with the conclusion in Ref. Satpathy et al. (2013). This relation was obtained through linear fitting, as shown in Eq. (18). Therefore, as the criterion parameters of the entrainment occurrence criterion, only one of them is needed to lay emphasis on subsequently. In this paper, re-submergence velocity (Vms) is taken as the research focus.(18)θ=114.21Vms-22.73

4. Analysis of influence parameters

4.1. Dimension analysis

By comparing Case 1 and Case 2, it can be seen that under the condition of same initial height of liquid level (Hl), the height of outlet position (Ho) has little influence, especially on the re-submergence velocity. The higher the outlet position is, the less resistance effect it has on the upward velocity of the fluid, which is more conducive to the occurrence of entrainment. This is mainly caused by the height difference between the initial liquid level and outlet position. In summary, the effect of the height of outlet position (Ho) on entrainment is so little that it is not taken into consideration for simplifying analysis. And the height difference ΔH = Hl − Ho = 20 mm remains unchanged in subsequent calculated cases of this paper.

In this paper, nine dimensional physical parameters have been studied, including the re-submergence velocity (Vms), the inlet size (hi), the width of hot pool (W), the initial height of liquid level (Hl), the inlet velocity (Vin), the gravitational acceleration (g), the liquid density (ρ), the dynamic viscosity (μ) and the surface tension coefficient (σ). The first one of them is dependent variable and the others are independent variables. The functional relationship formed by these parameters is not known previously, but a general expression can be built as follows:(19)Vms=f(hi,ρ,g,W,Hl,Vin,μ,σ)

If the inlet size (hi), the liquid density (ρ) and the gravitational acceleration (g) are assumed as the basic physical parameters, the values of dimensionless numbers composed of the basic physical parameters are all equal to 1:(20)π1=π2=π3=1

Since the inlet size (hi), the liquid density (ρ) and the gravitational acceleration (g) have been selected as the basic physical parameters, the dimensions of other physical parameters can be represented by the dimensions of these three basic physical parameters. Then, Eq. (19) can be expressed by a relation composed of six dimensionless numbers such as(21)π=Vmshixρygz

Since all of them are dimensionless numbers, each pair of numerator and denominator should have the same dimensionality. Take Eq. (21) as an example:(22)dimVms=dim(hixρygz)

If the dimensions of length, time, and mass are denoted as L, T, and M, then the above equation can be written into this form:(23)LT-1=Lx(ML-3)y(LT-2)z=Lx-3y+zMyT-2x

The exponents of a dimension at both sides should be equal, then x = 0.5, y = 0, z = 0.5 can be solved. Substitute it into Eq. (21):(24)π=Vmsghi

By the same way, π4=Whi, π5=Hlhi, π6=Vinghi, π7=μρhighi and π8=σ/ρhi(ghi)2 can be solved. According to the Buckingham’s π theorem, π, π1, π2, π3, …, π8 can constitute a dimensionless number relation for liquid fall type entrainment.(25)π=f(1,1,1,π4,π5,π6,π7,π8)

Associated with the above calculated results, it can also be expressed as:(26)Vmsghi=fWhi,Hlhi,Vinghi,μρhighi,σ/ρhi(ghi)2

It can be seen that the re-submergence velocity (Vms) is a function of various factors including Whi,Hlhi,Vinghi,μρhighi,σ/ρhi(ghi)2. The third term is Froude number (Fr), and it's not hard to find that ghi is actually a mark of the inlet velocity, having the same dimension as velocity. If ghi is represented by the characteristic velocity (V), i.e. V=ghi, Eq. (26) can be further written as:(27)VmsV=fWhi,Hlhi,VinV,μρhiV,σρhiV2=fWhi,Hlhi,Fr,1Re,1We

To sum up, the re-submergence velocity (Vms) is related to relative pool width (W/hi), relative initial height (Hl/hi), Froude number (Fr), Reynolds number (Re) and Weber number (We), indicating a direction for subsequent analysis. As for the specific expression, further study is needed to determine. For convenience and briefness, the five terms on the right side of Eq. (27) are respectively called pool width term, liquid level height term, gravity term, viscous force term and surface tension term.

4.2. Influences of parameters

4.2.1. Inlet size hi

By comparing the two groups of Case 1&3 and Case 4&5, it is obvious that the larger inlet size hi is, the less likely the entrainment is to occur. The turbulence intensity is defined as:(28)I=u′uavg=0.16Re-18where u' is the root-mean-square of the velocity fluctuations and uavg is the mean flow velocity. It can be seen that the turbulence intensity (I) reduces with the expansion of inlet size (hi) under the same velocity. The turbulence intensity (I) describes the variation degree of fluid velocity with time and space, so low turbulence intensity (I) is disadvantage to the occurrence of entrainment, which partly illustrates the rationality of judging entrainment by turbulence kinetic energy (k). It can also be seen from the comparison of results that when W = 100 mm, the simulation result of re-submergence velocity (Vms) with inlet size hi = 10 mm is larger than that with hi = 20 mm, but the rule is opposite when W = 200 mm. According to the previous dimension analysis, the expression of re-submersion velocity (Vms) is related to the relative pool width (W/hi). Thus, the supplementary cases with the variable of different relative pool width (W/hi) were additionally calculated, and the results listed in Table 4. The numerical results of re-submergence velocity (Vms) are drawn as Fig. 11, showing that the re-submergence velocity (Vms) in each case increases firstly, reaches the peak when the relative pool width W/hi = 10, after that decreases. However, it can be known from Eq. (27) that inlet size (hi) not only affects pool width term and liquid level height term, but also affects other items, so the inlet size (hi) is not suitable for quantitative analysis.

4.2.2. Pool width W

The cases with fixed inlet size (hi) and changing pool width (W) were added to observe the influence of pool width on the entrainment. The results are listed in Table 5 and the re-submergence velocities (Vms) are plotted in Fig. 12 with a horizontal axis of W/hi. The trends are basically piecewise linear. When W/hi < 10, re-submergence velocity (Vms) increases rapidly. When W/hi > 10 it changes to fall down gradually. The re-submergence velocity (Vms) is proportional to the inlet velocity (Vin) in cases with the same inlet size (hi). It can be concluded that a relative small pool width (W) will hinder the development of free surface velocity and a relative large pool width (W) is against to generate the upward fluid velocity. Both of these situations will also cause the effect of inhibiting the occurrence of entrainment. When the relative pool width W/hi = 10, the total inhibition effect of them is the least and the entrainment is the most likely to occur. 4.3. Expression of re-submergence velocity Vms

Through Eqs. (29), (30), the expression of the re-submergence velocity (Vms) based on the numerical simulation results can be deduced and can be further simplified and denoted as a general relation with empirical coefficients:(31)Vms=AWhi+BHlhi+CVinwhere A, B and C are empirical correction factors showing in Table 7. The previous supplementary Case 11 is a deviation case with a large inlet turbulence intensity mentioned above, and its results are highly uncertain. However, this empirical expression is also basically applicable to Case 11, which can still verify the rationality of the expression in a sense. It is noted that, in one hand in order to make the variation range of the relative initial height (Hl/hi) basically the same as Case 13 and 14, the Case 12 with the inlet size hi = 10 mm required lower initial height of liquid level (Hl). In the other hand, ΔH = Hl − Ho = 20 mm needs to be guarantees at the same time. As a consequence, the value of initial height (Hl) is limited. When the outlet position (Ho) is too low, most of the liquid entering from the inlet will flow directly out through the outlet without the process of hitting on the right wall and flowing upward to make the free surface swell, which is different from the occurrence process of the liquid fall type entrainment phenomenon studied in this paper. That is why the numerical simulation results in conditions of low initial height (Hl) in Case 12 are distinctly different from the calculation values of the above expression.

Table 7. The empirical correction factors for the expression of the re-submergence velocity.

Correction factorApplication rangeValue
AW/hi ≤ 100.03594
W/hi ≥ 10−0.00851
BHl/hi < 450.08520
Hl/hi ≥ 45−0.02117
CW/hi ≤ 10, Hl/hi < 450.15393
W/hi ≥ 10, Hl/hi < 450.59843
W/hi ≤ 10, Hl/hi ≥ 450.62376
W/hi ≥ 10, Hl/hi ≥ 450.96104

So far, the empirical relation of the re-submergence velocity (Vms) for the current fluid property has been obtained. Compared it with Eq. (31), it is found that the correction factors are associated with the fluid property (density ρ, dynamic viscosity μ and surface tension coefficient σ) and the characteristic velocity (V). Firstly, when geometry sizes (inlet size hi and pool width W) and initial conditions (initial height of liquid level Hl and inlet velocity Vin) are known, re-submergence velocity (Vms) of liquid fall type entrainment can be obtained by empirical relation. Then the re-submergence angle (θ) for the current fluid property can be calculated from the relation between re-submergence angle (θ) and re-submergence velocity (Vms). Finally, the conservative entrainment criterion can be used to judge whether entrainment will occur or not under different working conditions. The whole process of these provides a method for predicting the situation of liquid fall type entrainment.

5. Summary and conclusions

The process of liquid fall type entrainment on free surface of hot pool of SFR was studied by CFD numerical simulation in this paper. The parameters affecting the entrainment were qualitatively analyzed through the calculation results of the design cases, and the conservative criterion for liquid fall type entrainment happened between the two phases of sodium-argon was obtained: the entrainment will not occur when the re-submergence velocity is less than 0.56 m/s, the turbulence kinetic energy is less than 0.06 m2/s2, or the re-submergence angle is less than 37°, or Fr2•We is less than 55. The relation between the re-submergence velocity and the re-submergence angle is also known. After that, the supplementary cases were calculated to quantitatively analyze the influence parameters. From the results, the expression of the re-submergence velocity with correction coefficients was deduced so as to judge the entrainment situation under various working conditions. The whole process of analysis above provided a method of entrainment prediction for the safe operation of SFR.

It should be noted that the criterion was obtained under the current specific physical properties of fluids. However, the temperatures of sodium and argon are various in different SFRs and even changeable under various working conditions in a reactor, leading distinguishing physical properties of fluids. If entrainment prediction of each SFR with different physical properties is carried out in this way, the workload is heavy and the process is slightly tedious. Therefore, the viscous force term and the surface tension term in the expression of re-submergence velocity are needed to expand for obtaining a mechanism expression instead of an empirical one. This is a subject for future study.
